<p>The first thing you may notice from a picture of Siena would probably be the imposing Tower del Mangia, a beautiful combination of height and elegance. It’s just 7 meters taller than the tower of Palazzo Vecchio in Florence… and you can bet that was done on purpose! And that is understandable if we think that <strong>from the 13th to 15th centuries Siena was Florence’s main rival</strong> as the 2 cities were both trying to enlarge their territory. Overstepping centuries of rivalry, Florence and Siena upheld their elegant style: their skylines with medieval towers, reddish-brown rooftops, towering domes and Renaissance galleries are indeed picturesque and uncommonly enchanting.</p>

